[Event "London repertoire: Main system vs ...d5"]
[Site "OpenChessTrainer"]
[Result "*"]

{ The London setup against the classical ...d5/...e6/...c5 structure: Bf4
outside the pawn chain, the e3/c3/Nbd2 pyramid, then Ne5 and a kingside
plan. Same pieces, same squares, almost every game. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 (4... Bd6 5. Bg3 { Keep the bishop:
trading on g3 opens the h-file for the rook later. } 5... O-O 6. Bd3 c5
7. c3 Nc6 8. Nbd2) 5. c3 { The pyramid: d4 is overprotected before any
action starts. } 5... Nc6 (5... Qb6 6. Qb3 { Offer the trade: without
queens Black's only active idea is gone. } 6... Nc6 7. Nbd2) 6. Nbd2 Bd6
7. Bg3 { Again: never take on d6 for Black, make Black take on g3 and
give you the half-open h-file. } 7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. Ne5 { The London
knight: supported by d4 and the g3 bishop, it anchors every attacking
plan. } 9... Bb7 10. f4 { The Stonewall grip; Qf3-h3 and Rf3 lifts are
coming. } *

[Event "London repertoire: vs King's Indian setup"]
[Site "OpenChessTrainer"]
[Result "*"]

{ Against ...g6 the London turns positional: keep the pyramid, trade dark
squares carefully, expand on the queenside. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. O-O Nbd7 (6... c5
7. c3 { Solid: let Black spend time proving ...cxd4 helps anyone. } 7...
Qb6 8. Qb3) 7. h3 { A retreat square: ...Nh5 must never win the bishop
pair for free. } 7... c5 8. c3 b6 9. Nbd2 *

[Event "London repertoire: vs early ...c5"]
[Site "OpenChessTrainer"]
[Result "*"]

{ 2...c5 hits d4 before the pyramid exists. Stay calm: e3 and c3 hold the
centre, and the London pieces go to their usual squares. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 (3. c3 { Also fine; e3 first keeps the move
order flexible. } 3... Nc6 4. e3) 3... Nc6 (3... Qb6 4. Nc3 { b2 is
poisoned: 4...Qxb2?? 5.Nb5! traps the queen against Nc7+ and Rb1. } 4...
e6 5. Nb5 { The knight lands on b5 anyway: Nc7+ ideas force Black to
spend moves on defence. } 5... Na6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3
Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. O-O { Back in the main system: the early ...c5
changed nothing. } *
